<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There you have it folks. France doesn't need to pretend that it wants to develop a cash for oil deal with Saddaem. Money that Saddaem could easliy buy guns, tanks, missles, and tyranny with. Didn't you mention something earlier about containment and sanctions? Ohh my bad. Didn't know the same rules didn't apply when France get a big phat billion dollar check.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You're not too bright are you lurker?  Saddam doesn't need more money from the French- money was never the problem, he's rolling in it.  275 million dollars of American credit he received one year before the Gulf War goes an awful long way.  Money isn't an issue for domestic weapons programmes anyway, he has no need of it- as the supreme figurehead of a command economy he simply comandeers all the resources he needs, when he needs them.  Labour is awfully cheap in Iraq too, especially if the labourers have families and your name is Saddam Hussein.  To understand the French position- look at the way the Clinton administration approached China- not with gunboat diplomacy, but with trade and aid packages.  As a result of that, China is a far more democratic country, has opened up trade significantly and is well on the way to liberalizing fully.  The Soviet Union didn't switch systems under the threat of force, but through the incentives of trade and aid.  The French favour a similar policy with Iraq- China and the Soviet Union were arguably far more brutal regimes, but success of this approach there is likely to produce results here too.  That is the French hope- and I wish them every success in pursuit of that policy.<br>
<br>
  The issue isn't money at all anyway- but resources and production capability- both of which were irreversibly crippled if not utterly destroyed in the last inspection regime.  Scott Ritter, former US member of the UNSCOM inspection team under the last regime had <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.commondreams.org/views/030700-106.htm" target="top">this</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> to say about the state of Iraq's WMD programme- that was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>two years</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> before the current regime of inspections even started- after 10 years of the so-called &quot;12 years not disarming&quot; a key US member of that team says he's disarmed!  Whaddaya know...<br>
<br>
In addition, only a complete thicko would fail to see the obvious- that Saddam's is not a suicidal regime- and even assuming he had useable weapons of mass destruction + a delivery system (by no means proven)- <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>he would never use them</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Almost a hundred nukes within range of your entire country on British and American warships would deter anyone quite frankly.  The Soviet Union and the United States, both superpowers with vast nuclear arsenals deterred each other for the best part of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>half a century</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> without the principle protagonists firing a shot at each other in anger.  Are you seriously telling me that the US, a superpower can't deter a militarily backward nation crippled by 12 years of sanctions?  Think about it.<br>
<br>
Try and see past your own agenda-driven media painting French policy as Machiavellian lurker.  Their position is the most likely to disarm Iraq both from an effectiveness and a moral standpoint.  95% of Iraq's weapons programme was destroyed by inspectors- not bombs, not unilateral intelligence, not special forces, not by a war.  After 12 years of intelligence operations, air strikes, the Gulf war- the most effective means of disarming Saddam has been the inspectors- not these other means.  Inspections have worked, their techniques have improved, and they will work again given the time.  And there's no rush as I said, Saddam isn't going anywhere.<br>
<br>
A brief word on your sources regarding historical occurence.  Quoting Howard Stern (now there's a respected politically conscious public figure if ever I saw one)... is a joke.  Quoting that right-wing Zionist site that blatantly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>lied</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> about who attacked who first in 1967...is a joke.  That kinda destroys the credibility of any other information you've posted which comes from that site.  In fact I note <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> your information about Israel comes from a self-avowed pro-Israeli site.  Whoever wrote that piece on the Six-Day War lied cynically to mislead the opinion of the person who read it.  If such a person or persons are willing to lie once like that in their cause, I have no doubt that they'd be capable of the same again.  Try an unbiased or respectable source to support your key arguments lurker- the truth really does set you free.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I don't deny the US backed Iraq in the Iraq/Iran conflict. I don't deny the US probably trained terrorists in the Soviet vs Afghanistan conflict. I don't deny the US has a very shady history when dealing in the affairs of the Middle East.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If your going to hold America accountable for every nasty thing it did, look to Europe first<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The striking differences are two-fold-  firstly, European imperialism, while very nasty in the 17th through 19th centuries- did not shape the 20th century.  Our parents and grandparents did not live in the world of European imperialism- but they did live in the 20th century.  Thus, the actions of major powers in the 20th century is of significantly more relevance to the way in which the world shapes itself today.  This is blatantly obvious, it's a shame you ignore it cynically to further a vindictive snipe at a position you disagree with.<br>
<br>
The second major difference is that European governments have by and large learned their lesson- and drawn lessons from history.  Aggression and regime change hasn't entered the field of European foreign policy since the end of the second world war- with two notable exceptions, both which had disastrous effects- Eden and Suez in 1956, and De Gaulle and Algeria in 1961.  But again, the lessons were learned and policy moved on.  US policy never moved on- save for a blip in the 1970s with Jimmy Carter who engaged Anwar Sadat and signed the Camp David agreement.  Throughout the post-war era, from McCarthyism to the Vietnam War, to Pinochet &amp; the Shah of Iran in the 1970s, to Iran Contra in the 1980s- US policy has repeated the same mistakes over and over and over again.<br>
<br>
Well, what's wrong with drawing lessons from history may I ask?  It clearly would save time, money, effort, and above all human life.  The following example is somewhat bare to the bones and light on specific details, but the underlying principle is one I believe is sound, so please bear with me.<br>
<br>
  Consider the history of the Suez crisis of 1956 and the political aims surrounding that badly thought-out policy following Nasser's nationalization of the canal.  Churchill during the second world war had brought Britain out of the era of colonial rule into a self-sufficient capable state, a superpower in its own right, a permanent member of the Security Council.  Anthony Eden's disastrous attempt to capture the Suez canal ultimately resulted in Britain being dismissed as an imperial power, and effectively sidelined politically for almost 3 decades in the international community.  It wasnt' until Thatcher's second term that we were able to effectively take the world stage without being ignored and denied cooperation on key issues because of such a fundamental mistake of more than 30 years ago.<br>
<br>
Consider the recent history of US foreign policy and compare it- Clinton brings the US out of an era of regime change, support for dictators and cynical exploitation of other nations for national interest.  The Middle East peace process was never closer to finalization than when two Presidents who believed in the diplomatic process (Carter and Clinton) helped forge respectively- the Camp David Agreement and the Oslo agreement.  Hasty military action, regime change and short-sighted policies akin to these were scrapped in favour of a diplomatic approach of engagement.  The Good Friday agreement in Northern Ireland, resolution of crises in the Balkans, constructive engagement of China and North Korea, positive commitment to international treaties on the environmental, disarmament, landmines and a comprehensive conditional aid programme for Africa including debt write-offs.  <br>
<br>
All these policies yielded a greater feeling of security and stablility for the regions concerned and the international community as a whole.  All those policies have been scrapped by the Bush administration.  Regime change is back in the agenda, coupled with pre-emption, a dangerous cocktail that is in danger of isolating US policy even more severely than what happened to Great Britain after Suez.  It is a foreign policy package that will play directly into the hands of terrorists, swell their ranks and strengthen their resolve- it makes the world a more dangerous place than it is now.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The point is, the US does what it has to do to keep America safe.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
What it did prior to 11/9 with all due respect, did <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> keep America safe, it made America a target.  Aggressive policies that alienated the Palestinians, propped up the Saudi regime, pursued a hard line towards an Iran already crippled by the effects of a US-sponsored regime change and an Iraq crippled by sanctions.  That coupled with the blatant double standards of foreign policy in the region did not keep America safe lurker.  If it had- then 3,000+ innocent civilians wouldn't have paid with their lives in that brutal and uncivilized massacre.  <br>
<br>
The idea that you can catch or eliminate terrorists willing to sacrifice their own lives with force is a myth quite frankly.  Terrorists cannot be deterred the way Saddam Hussein and North Korea can.  The Israelis are certainly the very best in the world in terms of dealing with suicide bombers and state security in general- and even with aggressive inhuman policy in Palestinian areas they are unable to prevent these attacks.  In 700 years, British governments were unable to guarantee peace on their own soil by engaging the Irish republican movement with force- and that was dealing with terrorists unwilling to throw away their lives.  Ultimately it was by power-sharing and diplomatic compromise that the situation has been resolved- again, draw lessons from history.  <br>
<br>
Everything we know about this indicates that the only sane way to resolve terrorism is to address the fundamental injustices that drive people to strap bombs to their chests.  It isn't even an issue of religion by the way- Palestinians, whether Christian, Shia, Shi'ite or Ba'hai have all blown themselves up in Israeli civilian centers.  Yes it is distasteful to seemingly reward terrorism with a chance at diplomacy- but it's the only proven way to halt a cycle of violence.  There is always a price to be paid for peace- better that the price is a moral one than the lives of soldiers and civilians over decades.  <br>
<br>
To me, it takes greater courage <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to go to war, greater courage to be the first of the two dissatisfied parties to be willing to put violence to one side and start talking.  That is the sort of courage that is needed to secure a safe future for the children of the Middle East, and indeed our own children.  I fully accept that I am in a minority in thinking this- we are a fundamentally violent species, at times seemingly violent against all reason.  Yet if you are in a minority of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>one</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->- the truth is still the truth.  History is littered with nations that freed themselves of oppression with violence- only in two were freedom achieved with peace.  Mahatma Gandhi and Nelson Mandela never picked up a weapon, but they fought with greater courage and conviction than any soldier I've ever seen.  Let's see that courage from our leaders in their approach, and we will see a peaceful resolution to this crisis, in time to the Middle-East peace process- and eventually to terrorism itself. <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
