<br>
Thought about it...and I'm scared if Saddem gets WMD.  Would he attack the US?  Probably not.  But he might use that nuke on Israel or any other surrounding country he can't get his way with.  That folks, is a powder keg waiting to explode.  Let's admit here please that the Middle East could care less if Iraq destroyed Israel.  If Saddaem attacked Kuwaitt, he sure as hell would attack Israel AGAIN if he has the time, weapons, and opportunity.  The US won't stand idle if Israel gets thumped.  As I'm sure France, Turkey, Saudi, etc etc, will all jump into the fray.  And Saddem is just the type of person who might start a mess like WWIII.  Think about it.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote from Taranna:<br>
The striking differences are two-fold- firstly, European imperialism, while very nasty in the 17th through 19th centuries- did not shape the 20th century. Our parents and grandparents did not live in the world of European imperialism- but they did live in the 20th century.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I find it amusing you actually think the 18-19 century did not shape the 20th century.  Your narrow tunnel vision of a 100 years needs expanding.  <br>
<br>
The distrust and problems between Islam and Christianity take place before the 20th century.  The colonial rule and oppression by Europeans on the world takes place before the 20th century and influences how these former countries view the West.  Culture, values, music, beliefs, diplomacy, lessons, all these things evolved before the 20th century.  It really is a shameful shortsighted élitist attitude to think that past actions of a country from a century before are not remembered by the former oppressed population of today, and hence are of no consequence.<br>
<br>
You know why Israel was created.  Supposedly a safe haven from the constant anti-Semitism directed towards them from the world throughout history.  <br>
