<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I backed what howard stern stern said with creditable sources. Do you deny what he mentioned as false?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yes, categorically.  I see no reason for a grain of truth in any of his remarks- his purpose is to say what will make him popular and gain him listeners- his agenda has no accord with the truth or integrity, merely money.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is NO DISPUTING that Israel attacked first in 1967. But do you deny your own source that the Middle East was about to attack Israel in 1967? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You're missing the point here I feel- for a start- the source you quote is biased beyond belief, you admit this.  It has a vested interest in painting a good picture of Israel- such a source can hardly be credible in its presentation of the facts.<br>
<br>
The other point you seem to miss is that whether those forces attacked Israel or the other way around- Israel would have won.  Their forces were better prepared, trained and outfitted (primarily through US funds and military equipment).  The issue I'm pointing out is that Israel's response was neither proportional nor legal.  Consider the Indo-Pakistan conflicts- India saw off the threat of a Pakistani invasion- occupied a third of Pakistan- and then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>withdrew</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Why did they do this, a warmonger like yourself might ask?  They were the sole nuclear power on the subcontinent, they'd subjected the Pakistani army to a total and humiliating defeat, the land and resources were there for the taking.  <br>
<br>
The answer is simple- if you infringe on another nation's sovreignity, violate the UN charter and fly in the face of the very idea that a nation's identity and land are sarcosanct- then you risk completly undermining the international order.  It's the same reason Britain didn't decide to invade and occupy Argentinian soil during the Falklands war- it would be neither moral, nor politically acceptable to the international community for such a barbaric and imperialist response to have been initiated.  Israel is illegally occupying land lurker- you can spin that any way you want- but them's the facts.  The Golan heights belong to Syria- point me to a single point of law that says otherwise.  The West Bank belongs to Jordan- show me a single treaty or point of law that says otherwise.  The same is true of the Gaza strip belonging to Egypt.  Israel has absolutely no right from any civilized viewpoint to still hold onto these lands.<br>
<br>
You may paint the surrounding nations as aggressors- but you're clearly living in the past there- wake up and smell the coffee.  Syria, Lebanon, Egypt and Jordan <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> accept Israel's right to nationhood currently- that is their stated diplomatic position.  Granted, that wasn't the case 40 odd years ago- but rather a lot's changed since then wouldn't you say? :P  Given that their position no longer threatens Israel in any way militarily, give me one good reason why they shouldn't return the land they are occupying illegally.  Even better- show me <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>proof</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> not a biased position- PROOF- that there is a legal or moral case for keeping these other nations' lands.  And before you ask- no, &quot;Finders keepers ha-ha&quot;- and &quot;I get 2 k33p ur fat l3wtz y0&quot; are not acceptable as points of law.  We've rather moved on since the Middle Ages, fascinating isn't it.  Well, some of us have anyway :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Every terror regime and legit country needs money. Money to pay the workers, money to feed the troops<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Heh, Iraq is in complete trade isolation, there is no ERM, no connection with world markets- it has to function as an internalized economy in a fishbowl pretty much.  If Saddam wanted to he could just <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>print</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> more money.  There is no need to pay these workers in little slips of paper- very often brutal intimidation, threats against their families, and promises of substantial gifts and incentives (houses, other intangible resource structures) ensures loyalty far more effectively.  You seem to think Iraqis are actually paid, spend in consumer terms or function as any free market economy would.  Have you ever visited the planet Earth by any chance?<br>
<br>
As for what use money would be - you obviously aren't aware that Iraq's been under strict and heavy-handed sanctions for the best part of over a decade.  They are prohibited from buying <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>anything</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->- that is the severity of the sanctions imposed- that includes any dual-use technology or any precursors for WMD or anything that assists in those technologies.  The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>only</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> kind of export any nation is permitted with Iraq is food and medicine in exchange for oil.  The US has been the biggest exploiter of this scheme- as has been pointed out, it's far cheaper to commandeer or barter cheaply for oil than it is to buy it legitimately.  <br>
<br>
Even if Saddam had an endless supply of monies- it's all rather pointless if he can't even buy a toothbrush with it.  Containment is working lurker- he's being contained and being deterred just in case.  If containment isn't working- where is the evidence that it isn't?  If he's &quot;giving succour to terrorist groups and arming them&quot;- where's the proof?  I haven't seen a shred of it, just spurious claims founded on suspicion.  Innocent until proven guilty, evidence before action- those are fundamental principles of any  democractic system.  If in defending democracy you callously abandon those principles- then, putting it bluntly what's the point of being a democracy?  No person living in a free democratic society should be expected to prove their innocence- burden of proof always rests with the prosecution in any fair or judicial process.  Even if you're dealing with a hardened criminal who has certainly committed these crimes in the past- the burden of proof <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>still</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> rests with the prosecution and evidence regarding those past offences is inadmissible (at least in this country).  <br>
<br>
If these principles can be callously thrown aside in international affairs- how sure are you as an American that they won't be thrown aside on more important domestic issues?  Some might say this is already happening with the cynical exploitation of Guantanomo bay, and detention without a charge or legal advice currently signed into US law to hold &quot;suspected terrorists&quot;.  But going that extra step further, crossing the threshold of abandoning key principles of democratic justice has consequences- mainly that democracy has no meaning if you're willing to sacrifice its very heart and soul in its defence.  Aren't you afraid of that consequence?  <br>
<br>
What if the justice system in your country could arrest, convict and sentence you without a case having to be made?  What if that arrest, conviction and sentence were carried out based on suspicion- rather than proof beyond a shadow of a doubt?  That is what advocates of this war stand for- whether they know it or not- they stand for a system which only requires suspicion and impatience to declare war.  No case has been made, no threat has been established, no plan has been constituted for rehabilitation.  I would genuinely fear to live in a nation that upheld those principles in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>any</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> arena of policy.  And that is the state of affairs regarding Iraq- they are being asked to prove a negative, and the governments in favour of war haven't provided a single scrap of irrefutable evidence either that:<br>
<br>
1) The weapons exist, and in a useable condition<br>
<br>
or 2)  That such alleged weapons are being passed to &quot;terrorist groups&quot;<br>
<br>
and 3) That inspectors and experts on the ground feel that peaceful disarmament is no longer a reasonable option<br>
<br>
If any of these are manifested or proved beyond reasonable doubt, then you will find none more strongly in support of military action than myself.  Given that there is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>no</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> case beyond reasonable doubt and there is no proven threat and inspectors still feel they can do their job- why military action now?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>OMG, let's connect the dots folks. Iraq still has some unaccounted WMD. Iraq is required by the UN to be 100% disarmed, not 75%, not 90%. Iraq has the knowledge to build more WMD<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's like saying if the potential exists then it must be true.  Farcical argument- show me its proof, identify the veracity of such claims and I'll believe it.  Not before then.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Thought about it...and I'm scared if Saddem gets WMD. Would he attack the US? Probably not. But he might use that nuke on Israel or any other surrounding country he can't get his way with. That folks, is a powder keg waiting to explode. Let's admit here please that the Middle East could care less if Iraq destroyed Israel. If Saddaem attacked Kuwaitt, he sure as hell would attack Israel AGAIN if he has the time, weapons, and opportunity. The US won't stand idle if Israel gets thumped. As I'm sure France, Turkey, Saudi, etc etc, will all jump into the fray. And Saddem is just the type of person who might start a mess like WWIII. Think about it.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have thought about it, and it's bollocks.  Israel's own defence minister was quoted less than a month ago on a BBC Radio 1 interview saying that &quot;Iraq did not pose a substantial or imminent threat to the state of Israel- if they indeed posess materials necessary for weapons of mass destruction, in our evaluation these are not in a useable state to threaten the Israeli people&quot;  So- if the political head of Israel's defence forces don't think these alleged weapons are a significant or imminent threat- why does George Dubyah think they are?  Could it be *shock horror* that it's because it's not WMD he cares about especially, but regime change?  Noooooooo, surely not!  I mean, it was only a week after 11/9 that he announced that regime change in Iraq by force of arms was a &quot;desireable and achievable policy&quot;.  The more I hear, the less I'm convinced that WMD are even in the top 10 reasons the Bush administration marches inexorably towards war.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I find it amusing you actually think the 18-19 century did not shape the 20th century<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well that's because it didn't quite frankly- two world wars shaped the 20th Century- if imperialist dogma had shaped it we'd be living in a very different world.  Show me a single expert opinion that doesn't believe the world you and I live in today was shaped almost entirely by those two wars + the Cold War in geopolitical terms.  Those three wars- two hot and one cold fundamentally changed the entire cultural standpoint of Europe in *every* event.  Your spurious and farcical unproven or backed up claim that culture and political standpoints are influenced in any significant way by the happenings of 200 years ago is completely absurd.  In a nutshell:  prove it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If things can be resolved peacefully, I'm all for it. But if the terrorists your talking to don't want to talk, don't want to compromise, hold unrealistic expectations on powersharing, then nothing can be done.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well no- defeatism dogma like that would really mean that nothing could be done.  But, and here's the funny thing- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>it has been before</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  If you don't believe talking will work- then what's your alternative?  Read peoples' minds to discover who the terrorists are before they blow themselves up?  Remember- these terrorist groups aren't an elective government, they are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a mandate of the masses.  You've constantly harped on about the Middle East being a huge swell of one-minded opinion- yet you've provided no proof of this. <br>
<br>
 Most of the people I spoke to when I was there desperately <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>hate</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Hamas, and loathe what is being done in their name.  They also incidentally, hate their homes bulldozed and tankshells fired into residential areas- and the actions of a few extremists being forced on to the many innocents by Israeli government reprisals.  Israel on the other hand <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a government, it has the responsibility to act like one.  The current Israeli administration is acting on exactly the same level as the terrorists in terms of responding to senseless violence against civilians with...senseless violence against civilians!  I'm not taking sides on this either btw- Arafat's as shady as they come, and threw away the last best chance he had at a diplomatic solution.  <br>
<br>
To be quite frank, I trust neither of the principle protagonists in this- Sharon the Butcher of Sabra &amp; Chatila or Arafat the cynical ex-PLO man I have equal contempt for.  The problem is that your government and mine are overwhelmingly supporting Israel on this- our governments like it or not lurker <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>are</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> taking sides- that is NO way for an impartial arbiter of the conflict to behave.  And they're doing it with blatant double standards.  If Israel bulldozes innocent civilians' homes, then they're defending themselves from aggression- same for the Russians shooting innocents in Chechnya.  If on the other hand Saddam bombs the Kurds (who've over-run the northern third of his country and are a clear threat to his government)- it's an unbelievable human rights violation and our governments are suddenly appalled.  You tell me now lurker, man to man- is that either fair or consistent?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Saddem has the terms laid out in front of him. Fully comply now.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Iraq is a sovreign nation with charter rights and national interests- as are the US and Britain.  Your quoting the Bush administration's position on this is as irrelevant as if I were to quote the Iraqi position- they're both lying through their front teeth.  The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>only</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> impartial observers in this are the UN civil authorities- and especially the inspectors.  If they see a reason for inspections to continue, if they believe that inspections can produce results- THEY are the ones we should all be listening to.  They have absolutely 0 vested interest in either side of the position, and if they feel disarmament can be achieved via inspections with the level of cooperation they're currently receiving- then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>why go to war?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Based on the current facts, there is no reason to go to war.  &quot;Time is running out,&quot; say Bush and Blair- well why?  What's the almighty rush?  You've refuted a lot of my arguments lurker- but you've ignored the crucial points.  IE- where is the threat, and where is the rush?  Why isn't containment working?  If you can't answer those questions and come up with clear-cut proof, then there is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>no</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> case for war- none whatsoever.  I am not a pacifist, I am not against the judicial use of force.  That option isn't going anywhere, Saddam isn't going anywhere- there is not hourglass with sand running out, there is no pressing need for action.  If the criteria above are met- then I fully support the use of force, because at that stage all other practical alternatives (short of capitulation regime support a la Reagan) would have been exhausted.<br>
<br>
You can call me names lurker, you can spring little low-brow witticisms, you can even rely on biased sources for &quot;proof&quot; and suspicion as hard evidence for war.  But you can't dispute the key arguments, because there is no proof that supports you.  In fact, beyond your own bigoted convictions about the &quot;Middle East&quot;, there isn't a leg to stand on.  <br>
