A few side notes first.<br>
<br>
Side note 1:No fly zones<br>
They were not created by UN resolution. It is a bit rich to complain about iraq targetting or even shooting down planes in the no fly zone when those self same planes have been bombing targets in the no fly zone for the last 10 years. To draw a simplistic eq analogy - your guild has been pking me for 10 years and you complain when i finally pk one our your guys back?<br>
<br>
Side note 2: 1967 and 6 day war<br>
Israel carried out a pre-emptive act of self defence which was 100% legal as they were under imminent danger of attack from surrounding states (the surrounding arab states in 1967, 6 day war as israel did a fantastic job of defeating its foes in 6 days).  Pre-emptive as in, they attacked first, but only because they knew the other side was about to attack them. Eq analogy 2: the pker comes up and starts inspecting your gear, you attack before he mana burns you.<br>
<br>
Side note 3: West Bank / Palestine ownership<br>
The west bank / Palestine / Judea and samaria / Occupied Territories / Administered territories, call it what you will, are not owned by Jordan. there was what was called a  &quot;sovereignty vaccum&quot; in the west bank in 1967. Israel occupied them as part of a legitimate war of self defence. In my view the legitimacy of that occupation has long ended and Israel turned legitimate war time occupation into illegitimate annexation and colonisation. The west bank belongs to the palestinian people themwelves in exercise of their legal right to self determination.<br>
<br>
Main point - is an attack on Iraq justified?<br>
My gut reaction is no. And i can give you plenty of instinctual reasons why i say no:<br>
1. i don't like hypocrisy. Meaning saying one thing and doing another. Meaning propping up or supporting morally suspect regimes throughout the world but acting against them in one place.<br>
2. i dislike being told not to think. I don't like the mass media subservience to official government lines. I don't like being told that if i am not &quot;with&quot; the west, then i am &quot;against&quot; the west. I don't like propaganda spewed out from official sources.<br>
3. I don't like the demonisation of a people or of a religion, of the iraqis or of muslims, or of arabs in general.<br>
4. i dislike american imperialism gone wild, only this time with popular support. America has covertly and overtly intereferred in the fate of countries all over the world for years, oblivious to the rights of those concerned and all with the purpose of advancing america interests. The difference this time is that those who object are practically labelled &quot;terrorist sympathisers&quot; or supporters of despots like saddam hussein.<br>
<br>
Like i said, these are gut reactions and could be informed by inborn prejudices. I would like to cast them away and argue purely on the question at hand, which is, is it correct to invade iraq?<br>
There are 3 reasons advanced:<br>
<br>
1. He has links to al quaida, or other terrorist networks.<br>
The al quaide links are spurious at best. The actual hijackers came mainly from saudi arabia.  Upon being questioned, the best that Jack Straw, the British Home Secretary could say was that iraq provided an environment in which terrorists could thrive. That could be said about the UK providing a home for arab terrorists, the Republic of Ireland providing a home for Irish terrorists, the USA providing a home for south american terrorists, pakistan providing a home for kashmiri terrorists, southern india providing a home for sri lankan terrorists, the list goes on. A suspicion of this nature is no grounds for a war.<br>
<br>
2.  He has WMD and is prepared to use them.<br>
If i am honest enough with myself, i would have to say he probably does still have them. In addition, he has used them on his own civilian population in northern iraq in teh 1980s. No amount of anti war rhetoric will change this. He has also demonstrated a capacity for belligerence in invading kuwait. If i criticise the current nuclear powers for having nuclear weapons, then i must also criticise Irqa for having chemical ones and tyring to develop nuclear ones.<br>
Does this justify a war on iraq? Possibly yes. If these weapons are being loaded up now and being prepared to be fired at another country, then yes, step in and act in pre-emptive self defence. It would be fooolish to wait until the missile is in your own airspace before launching your own attack.<br>
However, this should be a last resort. There is no evidence that missiles are in the process of being fired over to neighbouring states. Neighbourign states are more likely to be against the war. Turkey (who it was claimed the US needed to defend) has actually refused permision for US troops to land there and base an attack from it. Even saudi arabia is expressing disquiet about being used as an airstrip for the western powers.  If the inspection and destruction programme is producing results, then it needs to be allowed to continue.  Far better a long drawn out inspection process with plenty of diplomatic fighting and debate going on than a war killing thousands of iraqis followed by an occupation of their country.<br>
<br>
3 Saddam is a bad man leading an oppressive regime.<br>
Yes, he is, and it is. Do we really need to start pointing the finger at other bad men in charge, and other oppressive regimes? Not liking someone, or them being &quot;bad&quot; is no reason in international law to justify an invasion. If it were, there would be constant warfare in the world. The UN charter doesn't accept it as a reason for war.<br>
<br>
Taranna has much more eloquently than me put forward the case for no war in the present climate. Even if i wanted to counter what he says, i would find it difficult. I am posting here to say that no, its not just one crazy brit with stupid ideas, there are lots of people all over the world with reasoned and principled objections to this war. <p>Bollix Braker <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Warlord <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Officer <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Celestial Empire <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=327563&quot;" target="&quot;_blank">Bollix's Gear</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=endymia>Endymia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 523<br> <font color=#333333>(3/5/03 8:40 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tar</span><hr size=1> I guess it all comes down to this: Taranna seems to say what a lot of euros think, and Drunkr for instance seems to say what the US thinks. Most of europe is against war (although everyone except France and Germany backs it up..  maybe afraid of sanctions on the long run or something).<br>
